Introducing the mGNO Converter
The mGNO token is a meta-token, similar to a Wrapped Token, which is created for staking purposes on Gnosis Chain. 1 GNO is equivalent and convertible to 32 mGNO. The mGNO converter is a simple to use and accessible tool for anyone holding GNO tokens.
mGNO contract on Gnosis: 0x722fc4DAABFEaff81b97894fC623f91814a1BF68
‍
Converting GNO to mGNO
1. Go to https://mgno.validategnosis.com/. Make sure your wallet is connected to the Gnosis Chain network, then click on Connect wallet on this page. 
We’ll use Metamask for this tutorial.
‍

‍

‍
2. Enter the GNO amount you would like to convert and click Convert. You can convert any amount of GNO that is available on your wallet, including less than amounts less than 1. 1 GNO is equivalent to 32 mGNO, so 0.1 GNO will convert to 3.2 mGNO.
‍
Please make sure to double check before clicking on Convert.
‍

‍
3. Sign and confirm 2 transactions in your wallet. The first is a free signature request to allow the application to make the conversion. The second will process the transaction. This will require a small amount of xDai fees to complete. You can claim free xDai to cover fees on GnosisFaucet.com.
‍


‍
4. The transaction should initiate and complete within a few seconds. Once completed, you can click on the following links on the page to check transaction details and add the mGNO token to your MetaMask wallet. 
‍

‍

Introducing the mGNO Validator Deposit feature
Since the recent launch of the mGNO Converter earlier this month, we have shipped a new feature called the mGNO Validator Deposit. 
‍
Traditionally, GNO is swapped for mGNO after depositing to the Beacon Chain. However, those participating in liquid staking services on Gnosis Chain are doing so by staking mGNO. Currently, staking mGNO is available on Ankr.
‍
If you wish to transition from liquid staking mGNO to running your own Gnosis Chain validator, this mGNO deposit feature makes the process possible as it allows you to make a direct deposit to stake. To run your own validator, learn more about the different validation methods on ValidateGnosis.
‍
Requirements
To make an mGNO deposit, your wallet must hold a minimum of 32 mGNO. If you have GNO, you can convert it to mGNO via the Convert tab. Refer to our step-by-step mGNO Converter tutorial here.
‍
Once you have the required mGNO, you will need to upload a valid deposit data file in the form of a deposit_data.json file. You can generate a deposit data file here.
‍
After successfully depositing mGNO, you can check the status of your deposit under the Validator Status tab. Here, you will need to upload the same deposit_data.json file to generate a Gnosis Beacon Chain link for your validator. This will allow you to monitor the details of your validator and its current status. Please note that it may take up to 24 hours before your new validator is registered on the Beacon Chain.

43a280a5-8136-4d25-b1d4-051f0b5269c8.text:
With our new series, Project Deepdive, we’re sharing conversations with teams that are building compelling projects and protocols on Gnosis Chain. Our first interview in the series is with Tellor, a decentralized oracle protocol that incentivizes an open, permissionless network of data reporting and data validation.
 
What is the genesis of Tellor?
We were working on an early DeFi project called Daxia that allowed users to create synthetic derivative tokens. We knew that if we wanted this to take place in a decentralized manner, we would need a decentralized oracle. At the time, though, nothing in the market existed. Chainlink was just a whitepaper and not decentralized, and everything else was either a centralized service or was very limited like the MakerDAO ETH oracle. So, we decided that we had to build it ourselves. Building the oracle protocol pretty quickly became our main thing, and we pivoted full-time to support it. This was the start of Tellor. 
‍
We launched to mainnet Ethereum in 2019, and Tellor began as a minable token. Miners would compete in PoW for the right to feed data on-chain for rewards. It took many updates and 2 major protocol re-works, but Tellor eventually became a robust and flexible system that utilizes a staking and cryptoeconomics-based model.  
‍
Why are oracles important?
Oracles enable smart contracts to execute functions based on real world events.  This opens up a whole world of use cases for these programs, ranging from insurance to dynamic NFTs, with the most popular use case being decentralized finance. Oracles feed asset prices to the whole of DeFi, and when oracles go bad, a lot of money can be lost. This is why it’s essential to have oracles as robust and decentralized as the blockchains they’re built on top of.
‍
What product does Tellor offer and what are the goals for these products?
Tellor is a censorship-resistant, do-it-all oracle that combines flexibility with full decentralization. We aim to ensure that data can be provided by anyone and checked by everyone.
‍
In addition to the commonly requested spot price feeds, we also have a number of more custom feeds that have been built, and new ones can be created permissionlessly. For example, we have a random number generator, a gas price oracle, EVMcall (which bridges on-chain data from one EVM chain to another), and a Snapshot oracle. You can see a visual representation of Tellor’s oracle feed on feed.tellor.io to get a sense of the oracle data that are being reported. 
‍
The goal is for the protocol to be used as a public good, applied to whatever off-chain data needs your project has. 
‍
What is Tellor’s value proposition compared to other oracle providers?
Building a truly decentralized project is impossible if you rely on a centralized source of data. Simply put, you either care about that or you don’t. The way the space is evolving, there’s a line being drawn; one side is building fintech 2.0, while the other side is designing projects to be censorship-resistant. Tellor falls in the latter. We offer projects a key piece of censorship-resistant infrastructure that is pivotal for a wide range of use cases. 
‍
We are much more of a “protocol” than more popular oracle services out there, and that's where we see the space trending. Decentralization aside, the flexibility of Tellor, which allows users to specify very customizable data requests, has been very attractive to users who can’t find what they need in competing oracles.
‍
Who are your targeted users/customers?
Our most common users tend to be DeFi protocols that operate in the lending space, stables, and derivatives. Additionally, the customizability of our protocol has been attractive to projects that need data of more obscure or long-tail assets, things that aren’t provided by the “Walmarts” of the oracle world. 
‍
What’s on the roadmap for 2023? 
“Tellor everywhere.” Our goal for 2023 is for Tellor to be deployed everywhere users want it, like Gnosis Chain for example.
Build out more unique and specialized oracles feeds
Increased cryptoeconomic security (stay-tuned!)
‍
What type of projects are you interested in collaborating with?
Anyone who thinks decentralization is cool AF is someone we enjoy talking to. We’re looking to collaborate with groups building new use cases and exploring great ideas for oracles.
‍
For projects that are looking to integrate Tellor, they can start with the Tellor Docs page or the Tellor School workshop series on Youtube. You can think of Tellor as a smart contract on Gnosis Chain, and you simply want your smart contract to read another smart contract. It’s relatively easy for any Solidity developer. There’s a whole test package built out to help you test reporting values, and, how you can then move over to Gnosis Chain’s Chiado testnet to test on a sandbox environment. Feel free to reach out to us and we’re happy to walk you through the whole process.
‍
What are your experiences building on top of Gnosis Chain?
As an EVM, Gnosis Chain was certainly easy for us to deploy on. But more importantly, it fits with us on an ethos level. We felt like we were part of the same tribe, and we were treated that way throughout the process of coming over.  
‍
Building on Gnosis Chain was easy and straightforward. We didn’t need technical support, and that's the standard you want. We’ve built on several other chains, and Gnosis Chain is definitely on top as far as making it easy to build. You have a token bridge, native data bridge, free RPCs to use, and you have a block explorer that works. While a lot of chains claim they have the following, in reality they actually don’t. We’re excited to see what people build on Gnosis Chain and how we can facilitate projects in the ecosystem.
‍
You can reach out to the Tellor team or stay tuned in their community:
https://twitter.com/WeAreTellor ‍
https://discord.gg/n7drGjh

813f7b97-7dda-4faa-b039-499edb75993c.text:
Welcome back to our Project Deep Dive series, where we share conversations with teams that are building compelling projects and protocols on Gnosis Chain. Our third interview in the series is with Mithraeum, an on-chain strategy game designed as an eternal world and built on Gnosis Chain. 
‍
What is Mithraeum?
Mithraeum is a pure on-chain grand strategy game with a strong emphasis on players’ social interactions. It is a virtual world and an infinite game/autonomous world, where players can develop settlements, trade resources on the market, create armies and raid other settlements. Such an environment opens opportunities for diplomacy and social activity, with every player having the power to alter the game dynamics and influence the situation. 
‍
After a successful Alpha release, Mithraeum is currently on beta in what we call the “Bronze Age” stage, a series of limited public tests where the Mithraeum community tests and validates hypotheses related to the game design. 
‍
In the game, a player starts as a Mithraeum ruler, an owner of a settlement, and from then on, the player's every decision can alter the dynamics of the game. You can read more about the game mechanism here, and to play the game, you will need to wait until the next tournament is live. 
‍
Subscribe to our Discord and follow us on Twitter to stay tuned for updates.
‍
How did Mithraeum start and how did you get to where you are today?
The idea to create a game in the genre of the grand strategy that is fully on-chain came to our founder Bohdan Melnychuk back in 2017. A few years later, he proposed that we attempt to create a simplified version of the idea during a weekend hackathon. We generated numerous ideas and even won several prizes at the event. About a year later since the hackathon, we gathered the team and embarked on developing an elaborate, advanced version.
‍
This was during the pre-GameFi, pre-NFT era, and we wanted to create a game for educational purposes. Our goal was to introduce more people to the potential of blockchains through gamification of the educational processes.
‍
Despite fluctuations in the industry, we have remained steadfast in our original concepts, maintaining full on-chain integration and promoting social interactions within the game. Our sustainable economic model was established prior to the downfall of many GameFi products which adopted Ponzi schemes. We have devoted significant effort to translating DeFi's familiar blockchain mechanisms into formats recognizable to traditional gamers, thereby bridging the gap between the two worlds.
‍
What are Mithraeum’s goals?
The ultimate goal of Mithraeum is to become a natural simulation of the economic, political, and social processes that we can observe in the real world and the problems that blockchains are designed to solve. Since the success of a player is directly related to how they come up with solutions to problems related to these processes, we expect Mithraeum to become a game-theoretic playground for future blockchain primitives, primarily related to coordination and organization, such as DAOs.
‍
What is On-chain Gaming and why is it important?
On-chain games are games that are built entirely on the blockchain and use the blockchain as the primary infrastructure for gameplay. These games utilize smart contracts to create a trustless gaming experience, which allows for greater transparency and fairness. The use of blockchain technology also allows for the creation of unique digital assets that can be owned by players and used across multiple games in a composable manner, creating a new paradigm for in-game economies. 
‍
Furthermore, on-chain games have the potential to create a new kind of gaming experience that is not limited by the constraints of traditional game development, and which can be fully customized and modified by the players’ community. Overall, on-chain games represent an exciting development in the gaming industry that we believe can revolutionize the way we play and interact with games.
‍
We recommend reading the following articles to dive into the topic:
On-chain Gaming: Principles for Building Viable Systems
Pureplay On-chain Games
Infinite Games
Digital Physics in On-Chain Games
‍
What is your value proposition compared to other on-chain games?
To date, Mithraeum is the sole on-chain grand strategy game that integrates players' social interactions as a fundamental part of the gameplay process.
‍
What’s on the 2023 roadmap?
In 2023, our focus is on enhancing the technical aspect of the game by supporting player-developed modules, introducing new gameplay mechanics, and elevating the game's visual appeal. Our aim is to improve both the appearance and gameplay to a new level. After engaging with our players, we identified the need to reduce hardware requirements, which is also a priority on our roadmap.
‍
We ran the Mithraeum Tournament Bronze Age III tournament at the start of the year with a reward pool that reached over 10,000 xDai. We strive to organize more tournaments, beta tests and receive feedback for newly introduced mechanics from the community this year.
‍
On that note, we would like to invite readers who have tried the game to participate in our feedback survey. Your feedback is crucial to helping us understand how we can improve our product and provide a better experience for our community.
‍
Who are your target users?
While Mithraeum is open to all types of players, it primarily appeals to individuals who enjoy the intricacies of diplomacy and excel in achieving strategic goals on the edge of conflict. These are players who are willing to think outside the box, using methods such as botting, collaborating, bribing members of rival guilds, and even spreading rumors or misinformation.
‍
On a side note, our friends at Gnosis Builders have built tools that make it easy to play Mithraeum, you can get free xDai to cover gas fees on GnosisFaucet, buy xDai to purchase settlements in the game on BuyxDai.com. If you experience issues with the Gnosis Chain during gameplay, you can try switching your RPC into Gateway.fm’s RPC.
‍
What type of projects are you interested in collaborating with?
Our team is keen on partnering with other on-chain projects that can provide relevant technology for the Mithraeum world or contribute to the development of the on-chain gaming community. We also welcome those who wish to create modules to enhance the gameplay. In fact, if we come across the right individuals with sufficient interest, we may offer grants or other incentives to support their involvement.
‍
What has your experience of building on Gnosis Chain been like? 
The game benefits from Gnosis Chain's inexpensive transactions and a pre-existing niche community established by other entirely on-chain games. We encountered technical difficulties upon the last tournament’s launch that appeared to stem from our community, suggesting scalability could become problematic if we increase the player base tenfold. However, Gnosis Chain and Gnosis Builders assured us that technical scalability won't be an issue in the future.
‍
Stay tuned in the Mithraeum community:
Mithraeum Twitter
Mithraeum Discord
Mithraeum Telegram

A guide to GnosisPools.info
‍
The recently launched GnosisPools.info is a great tool for Gnosis Chain validators looking to monitor their performance. GnosisPools.info aggregates validators run by exchanges, companies, pools, and operators into a helpful dashboard that allows anyone to track their activity, giving insight into which validators are active, inactive or under performing.
How to monitor your validators using GnosisPools.info
‍
If you own or wish to track an address owning 200 or more validators running on Gnosis Chain, you can easily monitor the aggregate status of these validators with GnosisPools.info.
Simply identify the deposit address that is paired to your validator keys. This will be the address used to stake your GNO with the validator deposit contract.
Once you know the address, navigate to GnosisPools.info where you can use ctrl(cmd)+f to search for the first 6 characters of the address.
You can now click on the address in any of the charts to isolate its data, giving you a clear look at the validators’ status and performance.
Monitor how many blocks these validators have proposed in the last epoch, how many blocks were missed in the last epoch, as well as the percentage of validators under that address which are inactive.
If you own 10 or more validators and wish to see them monitored on GnosisPools.info, head over to the instructions at the bottom of this post.
‍
Understanding GnosisPools.info Metrics
‍
Overview Metrics
GnosisPools.info shares a few chain-wide metrics to give validators a snapshot of the current network. See the current GNO price and the value of staked mGNO, as well as the total number of validators, monitored validators, slashed validators and monitored validator pools on Gnosis Chain.
‍
Proposed Blocks per Epoch
Use the “Proposed Blocks per Epoch” chart to track how many blocks were successfully proposed by validators, attached to a specific deposit address, over a given epoch. As a validator, this metric can help give you an idea as to your performance in terms of earning rewards.
‍
Missed Blocks per Epoch
Use the “Missed Blocks per Epoch” chart to track how many blocks were “missed” or unsuccessfully proposed by validators, attached to a specific deposit address, over a given epoch. As a validator, this metric can help you spot when your validators are underperforming and missing out on rewards.
‍
% of Inactive Validators
Use the “% of Inactive Validators” chart to track the amount, if any, of inactive validators, attached to a specific deposit address, during a given period. As a validator, this metric can help you spot potential issues with your validators that have caused them to go offline.
‍
Want to see your validators monitored?
If you own or control 10 or more validators on Gnosis Chain and wish to see them monitored on GnosisPools.info, DM us on Twitter to request to have your address added to the active tracking list.
‍

‍Introducing d14n.info
We are excited to announce the launch of d14n, a product by Gnosis Builders that measures the decentralization of Gnosis Chain and Ethereum's networks in real time. This tool is a comprehensive dashboard that allows you to monitor the state of decentralization using the Nakamoto Coefficient as the primary measure. As we continue to support Gnosis Chain in its mission of becoming the most secure, resilient, and decentralized blockchain, we hope this is a valuable tool to provide insights to collectively maintain the network’s health and security.
‍

Gnosis Chain is committed to making it easy for anyone around the globe to run nodes and validators. At its core, it is important to have a diverse set of validators with nodes running across many countries. For more details on setting up nodes and running validators, head over to ValidateGnosis.com 


Understanding d14n Metrics
Measuring decentralization is a difficult task, but there are several key metrics that can be used to determine how decentralized a network is. Using d14n is simple and intuitive. Simply visit the dashboard, and you'll have access to a range of these key metrics.

Measure of Decentralization
Nakamoto Coefficient
This refers to the minimum number of individuals or entities that add up to 33% of the Gnosis Chain network across different subsystems that make up the chain. When 33% of any subsystem gets compromised easily, the integrity of the network is at risk. The d14n dashboard shows the Nakamoto Coefficient across the subsystems of consensus client types, geographic distribution of validators, validator pools, and cloud service providers.

Network Subsystems
‍Number of Nodes
One of the most important metrics is the number of nodes on Gnosis Chain. This represents the number of discrete processes checking and maintaining the integrity of the chain following the PoS protocol. Currently, there are over 1400 nodes on Gnosis Chain.

‍

Active Validators
This refers to the number of validators that have made a deposit on Gnosis Chain. There are over 114,000 active validators securing the network right now.

‍
Geographic Distribution of Nodes
The distribution of nodes and their geographic location can help you better understand the level of geographic diversity across all nodes.


Consensus Clients 
The number of consensus client types and their distribution across GNO nodes can help you understand how reliant the network is on each client type.


Validator Pools
The number of pools and the distribution of GNO between them can help you understand the level of decentralization between staking pools.


Cloud Service Providers 
The number of cloud providers and the distribution of GNO validators between providers can help you understand how reliant the network is on each service.


By measuring these, d14n can help identify potential vulnerabilities, ensure that no single entity has too much control, and provide assurance that the network is operating as intended.

What is Gnosis Chain?Gnosis Chain is an EVM-compatible Layer-1 blockchain that aspires to be the most secure, resilient and credibly neutral blockchain, buttressed by a deeply decentralized network secured by over 100K validators.For more technical information, please refer to Gnosis Chain documentation.
What is PoS (Proof-of-Stake)?Proof-of-Stake (PoS) is a consensus mechanism for processing transactions and creating new blocks in a blockchain. Staking is when you pledge your coins to be used for verifying transactions. The same PoS implementation underlies both Gnosis Chain and Ethereum's consensus mechanism, except for a few differences outlined here.For more in-depth information about PoS, please refer to Proof-of-stake (PoS) | ethereum.org.
You can run a validator in two ways:
Delegated StakingA liquid staking provider takes token deposits, stakes those tokens, and gives the depositor a receipt that is redeemable for the staked tokens. The receipt represents those staked tokens that can be traded or used as collateral elsewhere. There are two advantages of using liquid staking:
You will get a staking token that can be reused in other DeFi services.
You don't have to meet the minimum requirements of 1GNO. Any amount of GNO is acceptable.
Plug and Play SolutionYou can purchase pre-configured hardware and have your validation node(s) running with just a few clicks. Minimal technical knowledge is required.Currently, there are two vendors in the market:
DAppNode (from 1,283.00 €) (HOPR model)
AVADO (from 1,600 USD)

Delegated Staking
Acquire GNO:If you don't have GNO already, check out https://buyxdai.com/gno to see how you can get some. Liquid staking allows you to stake fractional amounts of GNO.
StakeWise Liquid Staking:StakeWise supports liquid staking on Gnosis Chain. Gnosis Chain users who delegate their GNOs/mGNOs to Stakewise will be able to receive sGNO to be used in other protocols in the Gnosis Chain ecosystem. Additionally, staking rewards accrue daily in rGNO tokens. The current staking fee taken from the StakeWise is 15% (Dec, 2022).
Read more
Stake Now
Ankr Delegated Staking:Ankr supports delegate staking on Gnosis Chain. Gnosis Chain users can use mGNOs to delegate on Ankr Staking. The current APY is 13.62% (Dec, 2022). If you don't currently have mGNOs, the GNO to mGNO converter will be available soon.
Read more
Stake Now
Setup Tutorial for Preconfigured Hardware
Acquiring GNO:You will need at least 1 GNO (32mGNO) to stake and run a validator node. If you don't have GNO already, go to https://buyxdai.com/gno to see how you can get some.
Setup Guide for DAppNode:DAppNode is a plug-and-play solution for validation nodes on Gnosis Chain. Minimal technical knowledge is required. Simply follow the setup guide to start your node.Learn how to setup DAppNode
Setup Guide for Avado:Avado is a plug-and-play solution for validation nodes on Gnosis Chain. Minimal technical knowledge is required. Simply follow the setup guide to start your node.Learn how to setup Avado

1 - Application Overview
Gnosis Auction is a decentralised platform that provides an avenue for a fair and transparent token price discovery. The marketplace supports the sale of ERC20 tokens on the following networks:
Ethereum Mainnet
Gnosis (Formerly known as xDai)
Polygon
Mumbai (Polygon Testnet)
Goerli (Ethereum Testnet)

For each of the following networks, users can launch an auction through this GitHub repo or through this Safe app. 

1.1 - Overall App Architecture



1.2 - Products we use for this Application:
The Graph Protocol - Hosted service for indexing auction info
Lit Protocol - To encrypt and decrypt signatures for private auction
Pinata - To store our signature data for private auctions on IPFS

2 - Deployment Details
2.1 - Frontend Deployment:
The current website (based on the old repo) is deployed at https://gnosis-auction.eth.link/
However, our test website (based on our latest up-to-date repo) is deployed at https://gnosisauctiontestv1.netlify.app/
The frontend is built on React Typescript. The components are ordered in a standard format.
2.2 - Middleware
The frontend communicates/updates with the backend through Graph APIs. These APIs were tested and developed on Graph Studio and are essentially GraphQL queries. These APIs are available in the folder “src/api/”

The graph QL queries are stored in Queries.ts and are exported and executed in the “AdditionalServicesApi.ts”. If you want to test out any sample queries, please head to one of these subgraph studio links:Goerli:
https://thegraph.com/hosted-service/subgraph/gnosis-auction/ga-goerliGnosis:https://thegraph.com/hosted-service/subgraph/aireshbhat/gnosisauctionPolygon:https://thegraph.com/hosted-service/subgraph/aireshbhat/gnosisauctionpolygonMainnet:https://thegraph.com/hosted-service/subgraph/aireshbhat/gnosisauctionservicesMumbai:
https://thegraph.com/hosted-service/subgraph/aireshbhat/gnosisauctionmumbai
All the Graph QL entities that were deployed are available in helpers.ts. If you want to create a copy of this deployment to your own subgraph-hosted service, please clone this repo: https://github.com/Gnosis-Builders/gnosis-auction-graphand change the environment variables based on your own subgraph links. To know how to deploy a subgraph: https://thegraph.com/docs/en/deploying/deploying-a-subgraph-to-hosted/
2.3 - Backend Deployment 
Currently, our backend is deployed on the subgraph-hosted service under one of these two accounts:https://api.thegraph.com/subgraphs/name/aireshbhat/ {samplenetworkname}
Contains gnosis, ethereum mainnet, polygon and mumbai deployment
https://api.thegraph.com/subgraphs/name/gnosisauction/{samplenetworkname}
Contains goerli deployment.

In the future, we plan to migrate fully from the subgraph-hosted service to the graph indexer platform (directly deployed on Graph nodes using GRT)

2.4 - Other Services
One of the other key features of our application is the ability to launch and host private auctions. In Private auctions, the auctioneer can whitelist a group of wallet addresses to participate in their launched auction.

To ensure this Private auction process remains secure and decentralised, we are using Lit Protocol. Our private auction mechanism is as follows:
The auctioneer initiates the private auction and adds a group of whitelisted addresses
For each address, the auctioneer signs a unique signature which allows access to the auction smart contract
Each signature is then encrypted using Lit Protocol and stored on IPFS using Pinata
When a bidder visits the auction page, they will be asked to confirm an AuthSig transaction to verify their address
Once the transaction is confirmed and the wallet address is verified to be whitelisted, the unique signature is decrypted by Lit
The smart contract realises this signature as verified and refreshes the frontend to allow the wallet address to participate in the auction.











2.4.1 Diagrams for Private Auction
Auctioneer

Bidder



3 - Smart Contract Details

The smart contract here refers to the Easy Auction Smart Contract. The repo for the contract can be found here: https://github.com/Gnosis-Builders/ido-contractsGA has not made any changes to this Smart Contract and doesn't plan on doing so in the near term. 

For the auction platform, there are 4 key types of events we index from the smart contract into our Graph deployment:
NewAuction
Instantiate AuctionDetail entity
Store initial auction details. For eg, Bidding token, auctioning token, sell amount, buy amount...
If private, stores auctioneer address and allow list contract address
ClaimedFormOrder
Updates “claimedOrders” list in AuctionDetail
Removes the order from the list if the order has been claimed.
CancellationSellOrder
Remove order from all order lists
Update Clearing Price and Volume on each order cancel
NewSellOrder
Instantiate new Order entity
Added to list of orders in AuctionDetail
Store AuctionId in list of auctions participated by User
Update Clearing Price and Volume on each new order
NewUser
Initiate a new user and get details












4 - Graph Details

6 - Testing a Deployment
We test our auction platform on the Polygon Mumbai network (as of ). Please ensure you have deployed it properly by following all the steps in Section 5. 

It's important to ensure all testers have test MATIC to participate in test bidding, launching auctions and other initiatives.

To launch our own test auction, we use this website built by one of our genius devs: https://auctiontestsite.netlify.app/
The documentation to launch the auction can be viewed here: 
https://asper9.notion.site/How-to-initiate-an-auction-2f6fea503c564448af1f07872ec474b9
Once deployed you should be able to view your auction on your website deployment. Project Details
Name: Gnosis Auction
Project Industry: dApp for Token Sales
Post Category: Integration

Lit Spark Article
Gnosis Auction, a decentralised marketplace devoted to fair and permissionless token price discovery, is excited to partner with Lit Protocol in announcing Private Auctions. This collaboration aims to provide a secure whitelist mechanism to our auctioneers and for bidders to ensure a seamless transaction process on Gnosis Auction.

What is Gnosis Auction and how are Private Auctions relevant
Gnosis Auction is a platform that allows the auctioning of ERC20 tokens on the Polygon, Ethereum Mainnet and Gnosis chains. The auction platform was built to allow both auctioneers and bidders a transparent mechanism for identifying and selling tokens at a price determined by the community. 

Apart from being completely decentralised via the Graph protocol, one of our key features is Private Auctions. Here, we allow the auctioneer to limit their auction participation to a set number of wallet addresses. 
How does Lit come into play?
Prior to our full decentralisation on the Graph, Gnosis Auctions used to host our backend on AWS servers. As such for any private auction, we would typically store the whitelisted addresses in a SQL database which we would then cross-reference whenever a bid transaction was initiated. 

However, to achieve true decentralisation, we couldn’t store this data on our servers and we had to move to IPFS. But since IPFS is a public ledger how can we ensure that this data is encrypted and only decrypted when the correct/whitelisted address is demanding access? Enter Lit Protocol! 

With Lit, we could encrypt bidding access to specific auctions by an on-chain condition (in our case, wallet addresses defined by the auctioneer) to only limit the auction to a specific group of participants. Lit makes this all work seamlessly under the hood.

Well, how does it actually work under the hood?

Let’s start with initiating an auction. An auction is rendered “Private” when an auctioneer signs an auction contract function to be limited to a certain group of participants.  In such an event it then becomes the auctioneer's responsibility to sign the addresses that will have access to this auction contract. For example, the auctioneer of auction A signs a message for each user they want to give access to, where the signed message contains the address of A and the address of the user (let’s say B). 

This unique signature (based on each user address) enables bidding access as well as claiming auction rewards. This is handled effectively by our backend without any user intervention. 

After the signature for user B is generated, our Lit integration automatically encrypts and uploads the signatures to IPFS using Pinata. Success! A private auction has been launched.






What about the bidders? Let’s take user B again. Now, the auctioneer tells user B, “Hey, I started this cool token sale and I have only allowed you to take part! Check it out!”.

Once user B enters the auction page, the system will check if a signature exists for user B’s wallet address. Since user B has been granted access, the system will then ask the user to prove that they own the wallet, typically by an AuthSig transaction. Once the transaction is approved and the wallet address is deemed to be legitimate, our Lit integration then automatically decrypts the user signature data on IPFS. 

With signature data now available, the auction page refreshes to allow user B to bid on the token sale for auction A. [Here’s a flowchart for better understanding]



Let’s say a rogue user C, eavesdrops on user B’s conversation with the auctioneer. They may then try to bid on a token sale without approval. But jokes on them. Since the system is aware user C’s signature doesn’t even exist, they will not even receive an AuthSig transaction to approve their identity nor request Lit to decrypt their non-existent signature. 

Et voila, a safe and secure whitelisted auction!

That’s awesome!

Indeed! With our integration of Lit, token sales can not only be limited to certain buyers as per seller intent but also helps us to stay regulatory compliant by mandating a KYC-type process. Providing a fair and decentralised platform has always been the goal of Gnosis Auction and we hope to continue to build on this strategic partnership with Lit to power our dApp to the next level!
